@ThinkingandTinkering Might be the case... In praxis I very seldom seen an induction Motor without ballbearings because they are mostly for heavy duty like drive a washing machine or more - about 600 Watt and higher. 
It was for me number one to check the bearings: Just put a scewdriver nearby the bearing, hold one ear at the handle of driver and turn the rotor. In silence the bearing is ok - if not needs to replace. 
Step number 2 was to check the resistance curls vs. ground / motor housing. 1000 Ohm / Volt minimum.
